The Lawsuit They Are Writing for Themselves

AI, AGI Claims, and the Liability Gap Between Marketing and Reality

1. Introduction — When Marketing Becomes Specification

For the past several years, the leaders of major AI companies have made increasingly large public statements about what their products are and what they will soon become. These statements are no longer modest claims about productivity tools. They are claims about intelligence, general intelligence, the replacement of knowledge workers, and the transformation of the economy.

Jensen Huang has stated that intelligence is becoming a commodity — something like electricity or bandwidth.
Greg Brockman has stated that artificial general intelligence is perhaps 70–80% of the way there and may arrive within a few years, with the main remaining task being raising the reliability floor across intellectual tasks.
Dario Amodei has warned that AI could eliminate a large fraction of entry-level white-collar jobs in the near future.
AI companies increasingly demonstrate systems writing code, designing systems, and assisting in technical and professional work.

These are not trivial claims. They are not marketing slogans for a photo filter app. They are claims about replacement-grade cognitive capability.

And once a company publicly positions its product as replacement-grade intelligence, those statements stop being philosophy and start becoming something much more concrete:

They become specifications in the eyes of the public, investors, employers, and eventually regulators and courts.

