2. The Intelligence-as-Infrastructure Claim

If intelligence is becoming a commodity, as claimed, then intelligence is no longer a rare human trait — it is infrastructure.

But infrastructure has a definition in engineering and law. Infrastructure is something society relies on. Electricity, water systems, aircraft, medical devices, financial systems, and telecommunications networks are all infrastructure. These systems are not judged by their best performance. They are judged by reliability, predictability, and safety margins.

The defining feature of infrastructure is not that it works impressively.
The defining feature is that it works reliably.

If AI is now infrastructure — cognitive infrastructure — then it must be judged by infrastructure standards, not demo standards.

You cannot call something electricity and then defend it by saying the lights go out unpredictably but are “superhuman” when they stay on.

