3. The “Jagged Intelligence” Problem

One of the most revealing statements made by AI executives is the description of current systems as “jagged”: extremely capable in some domains, but still failing at simple tasks.

In research, that is interesting.
In a product marketed as intelligence, that is a warning sign.

In engineering, unpredictability is more dangerous than low performance. Engineers can design around a weak system. They cannot design around a system that is brilliant one moment and wrong the next without clear boundaries.

A calculator that is wrong 10% of the time is not a calculator.
A navigation system that invents roads is not a navigation system.
A medical system that hallucinates diagnoses is not a medical system.

So the question is not whether AI is impressive. It clearly is.

The question is whether a system described as general intelligence can be relied upon at the level implied by that description.

Because general intelligence is not defined by peak performance.
It is defined by reliable performance across domains.

The floor matters more than the ceiling.

