7. The Reliability Standard Problem

Physics, engineering, medicine, and aviation all run on the same principle:

A system is judged by how it behaves when it fails, not when it succeeds.

This is why aircraft are tested to destruction.
This is why medical trials take years.
This is why bridges have safety factors.

Reliability is not about being impressive.
Reliability is about bounded failure.

The current generation of AI systems does not fail in bounded, predictable ways. It fails in unbounded, confidence-preserving ways — producing plausible, confident, and sometimes incorrect outputs.

That failure mode is manageable in a writing assistant.
It is dangerous in a system marketed as general reasoning infrastructure.

The closer the marketing language moves toward “general intelligence,” the more that failure mode becomes a legal and professional problem rather than a technical curiosity.

